-- South African Stocks Decline, Snapping Two Days of Advances, Led by Anglo
-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 2010-11-05T12:14:13Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-05/equities-in-south-africa-retreat-bhp-billiton-gold-fields-harmony-move.html
South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  snapped two days of gains, dropping 113.49, or 0.4
percent, to 31,214.41 as at 1:58 p.m. in Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today:  Anglo American Plc  (AGL SJ), the second-largest mining
company in Africa, snapped two days of gains, falling 1.81 rand,
or 0.6 percent, to 328.20 rand. Workers at the company’s
Collahuasi operation in northern Chile went on strike after wage
negotiations failed.  Barloworld Ltd.  (BAW SJ), the world’s biggest forklift
dealer, declined 90 cents, or 1.7 percent, to 52.55 rand. The
company said it expects that earnings a share for the 12 months
through September will range between breakeven and a loss of 10
cents, compared with a profit of 3.22 rand a year earlier.  BHP Billiton Ltd.  (BIL SJ), the world’s largest mining
company, advanced for a second day, rising 50 cents, or 0.2
percent, to 268 rand. Copper in London jumped to a 28-month high
as the U.S. Federal Reserve’s bond-purchasing plan weakened the
dollar and boosted the economic outlook. Nickel and zinc also
gained.  Freeworld Coatings Ltd.  (FWD SJ), rose 10 cents, or 1.1
percent to 9.20 rand, breaking four days of decreases. The paint
company has had an unsolicited bid from Japan’s Kansai Paint
Co., a statement from South Africa’s competition authorities
shows.  Pan African Resources Plc  (PAN SJ), a gold exploration
company, climbed for a fourth day, adding 5 cents, or 4.5
percent, to 1.16 rand, the highest since April 2008. The company
said it signed an agreement with International Ferro Metals SA
Ltd. that will enable its Phoenix Platinum Mining Ltd. unit to
build a chrome tailings retreatment plant and start production
by the end of 2011.  To contact the reporter on this story:
